segments.text: During the war, did you ever have an experience where it seemed like one particular man was trying to kill you?
Every time I had a bullet shot at me, I thought they were shooting at me personally.
No, no, I never.
I felt they were all shooting.
at people.
It's an old joke that went along out there.
You're not worried about the bullet with your name on it.
You're worried about the bullet that says, to whom it may concern, is the one you have to be worried about.
That's an old joke.
But, no, what scared you, what scared me a lot, was you'd be sitting right next to a person, or laying next to a person.
You're firing at the enemy, and you can't see, and they can't see you half the time.
Then, he gets hit, and he's no more than two feet away from you.
And it kind of, afterwards, all over, he'd say, God, if I was just two feet over, he would have gotten me.
You know, and it makes it weird.
Or you're in an area and mortars are coming in, and a mortar hits another guy's hole where he's sitting.
He'd say, God, what if I was, if that mortar came, if the guy just held the mortar an inch higher, that would hit my hole, you know.
I never thought of him shooting directly at me, but he was weird.
During the space of the conflict, under the stresses,
Was there ever a situation where there was one specific man or you lost control and you wanted to get one guy or get anyone you could get after what had just happened?
Yeah.
The problem, you get so frustrated at times, especially when your best friend there gets shot or wounded or hurt or dies.
You won't take it out on anybody.
If I had the Vietnamese you hate after a while.
But that's at first.
I don't remember ever getting super mad to kill someone because, like a colonel or even somebody in our own unit or the enemy.
I would love to get a hold of them a lot of times.
I wish, a lot of times you kind of wish we could have just nuked North Vietnam.
That's about as angry as I got toward a person.
No one individually or one person in particular.
How was the psychology of the war on you?
There are many Vietnam veterans who feel like the VC were like shadows, unable to be hunted down.
They would be able to live off the land, bearing hardships, and then they could move in and out.
How did this affect you, and how do you think that the ability of the superior technology, the Americans, affected the VC mentality or the NBA mentality?
I never saw the VC.
The part of country I was in was the I Corps, which was North Vietnamese regular.
The way that the Vietnamese, the catches they had now, we were totally superior to the Vietnamese.
I still believe that.
The military, when I was there, was very highly trained.
They were there to do a job, and they could have.
I feel the main problem, again, is going back to politics, the idea that we could not shoot into certain areas.
And they knew that.
Before we caught in a fire support, we had to get, there's red areas, areas you could not fire into.
So they would say, sorry, you've got to move out some to shoot in that area.
But you're under fire.
You can't do that.
They also knew they could get into a temple.
A temple area starts shooting at you, but you can't shoot back.
I did not like that.
If I was a general head of the press, the first thing I would do is kick all the press out of Vietnam.
That made another problem.
We couldn't do certain things.
We couldn't go into certain areas.
We could not ask questions the way we would like to get information from the enemy.
They were shadows.
Of course, I got off the tangent.
I didn't even do that.
They had catches.
I don't think they were any more superior
I think a lot of people put their ideas way above what they really were.
They had things put away.
They had a distribution area right on the other side of the DMZ when we were up at, we call it Big Rock.
It is a place where we watched the Vietnamese on the other side of the DMZ.
They were there.
There's a staging area.
It's a staging camp.
I don't know how they worked there.
I don't know if they came down, stayed a couple of weeks or a couple of months, and moved back up into staging area, or they stayed their entire time down into I-Corps.
I don't know.
But I don't think they were that good.
I feel that they knew the jungle.
We didn't.
They had certain areas.
They controlled the jungle.
We didn't.
We controlled the cities.
They controlled everything else.
We would go out on patrol.
We would look for them.
They'll hit us.
Then we'll run back to the city, or go back, not run, but go back to the city.
But they controlled and held the jungles.
They held the rice paddies.
They held the farms.
We fought the war totally wrong.
I blame, again, politics and our State Department for that.
Scorched earth.
Scorched earth was a great idea.
They used the wrong chemicals to do that.
Again, if I was a smart man, I would not be a school teacher.
I would have been a general somewhere.
But they should have, if they would have gotten rid of the jungle, the CIA or the people, his intelligence, his advisors were right.
Get rid of the jungle.
They have no place to hide.
But how they did it was totally wrong.
And it didn't work at that.
They stopped using Agent Orange because it did not fulfill what they wanted to do.
They would have had to, whatever, I don't know, burn it down.
How should we have fought the war?
Nuke it.
No, I'm kidding.
I don't.
We could have tried out one of our new bombs on it to say it accidentally fell out of the airplane.

If we would have fought the war properly, that's hard because if I say we fought the war properly, the first thing we should have done is gotten rid of the entire government, the corruption going on in the system, which is not the military's problem.
The military doesn't go in and say,
General, we don't like your president.
We don't like the way your government is.
Get rid of it, and then we'll fight for you.
The military has to go in when the president tells them to.
I just feel that State Department blew it, and they tried to make the Army be blamed for it.
And that's totally wrong.
It wasn't their fault.
Get rid of the corruption first, and then you might have a chance.
The people then would have respected us a little more
or their own government.
They would have taken pride in their own country.
They didn't care.
They were so corrupt.
Who would want to take pride in a country that's corrupt?
I remember from your previous lectures at the high school here, you said that most Vietnamese were just neutral.
They cared about their rice paddy.
Yeah.
The farming area was that way.
I noticed the guys...
I go back to 1954 when Dinh Dinh Phu happened.
They were set up by the U.N.,
North Vietnam and South Vietnam, they will take and say, okay, anybody that wants to be communist, you know, go north, south, same way.
They did that in Korea, but the Korean had a different philosophy toward life than the Vietnamese.
Totally different type of people, but they thought it would work that way.
These Vietnamese believed their land was very important to them.
They didn't care what government they had.
They just wanted to make their rice or whatever they grew and live a very happy life.
They might have, they believed and they loved Ho Chi Minh.
Ho Chi Minh was a great hero to these people.
We, on the other hand, did not like Ho Chi Minh because he was the bad guy to us.
And it made it difficult because these, I believe that's who the VC were.
Well, I know that's who they were.
I didn't see it again.
We're talking just by hearing other people that were in two corps, three corps, and especially four corps, that they, at night,
They'd get out a gun, shoot one American, hide the gun, and back right into his field.
He did not like Americans.
Not that he didn't like us.
He did not want us there.
He wanted that to be one country again.
We were there stopping his country from being unified.
They're not a very smart people.
They're farmers.
They're just regular people.
They just want to be left alone.
We wouldn't.
And they did not like us for that.
So would you consider the American influence, in addition to the fact that the South is so corrupt, a major contribution to the resistance that would grow as long as the Americans were there?
I think that they believed the Americans, which it was, that the Americans caused the corruption, caused the collapse of respect for themselves.
And I believe the Americans did cause that.
The last I heard, the Vietnam War is still going on.
They just change sides every so often.
Different people try to take over.
South Vietnam, China now, I heard, is trying again to take over.
It's an area that is continuous.
Whoever's fighting will always fight for Vietnam.
Your great-great-grandchildren might be there again.
I hope not, but it could happen.
What is your strongest memory about Vietnam?
Bleeding.
No, no.
The strongest memory.
USO shows.
Dirty 8mm films that we somehow got in there.
R&R.
I don't remember too much about R&Rs, except I've got a lot of pictures out of focus.
Let's see.
The guys that I hung around with.
Things like that.
The bad parts of Vietnam, I don't want to remember.
It's not that I'm trying to blot them out.
It's just they were bad parts.
Vietnam to me was three years of my life that I grew up with.
I have a lot of respect for the military because I grew up there, and I thought that I owed the military something.
So that's why anything to do with the military today, I believe it should be stronger.
I think boot camps should be ten times harder than what they have today because...

i know what i had to go through some of the dumbest things in the world but again it it helped me understand myself by doing these dumb things looking back at the time it's just stupid but looking back it really helped me um the the friendliness of the military sometimes and you also you got the quacks in there you got the kooks uh the poker games the uh short sheets you've got all that uh putting salt in the shower heads uh

just all kind of things that they would do to you and of course you do it back to them uh meeting other guys i but the killing in the at that part i don't like to remember too much of i just like to forget that some guys that that's all they live for is to say how bad it was in vietnam and it was pretty bad but then again i try to remember the fun parts the uh hill ford isn't it's not as bad i can't i have a fond memory not of vietnam but of the camaraderie
So there was a strong feeling of even family between the two?
Oh, yeah, yeah.
Some people got very, very close.
I have a friend that we became super, super, super close.
We went on one R&R together.
As we can say, as we would have said together, between us two, we were arrested in every country we went to.
Drug and disorderly, of course, but then what they'd do is
As a military, they'd say, okay, sober up, and we say we promise.
And they said, don't get drunk again, we promise.
You know, they let us go, and a couple hours, we're back there again, you know, saying the same thing.
But again, it's a place to blow off steam and take total obnoxious people out of ourselves for a few hours or a few days.
Again, all pictures were almost, most of them are out of focus, and that only shows me how great of a time I had, I guess.
In Richard Nixon's book, No More Vietnam... Who's he?
Okay, I'm sorry.
He claims that we actually won the war physically, and then we let the South fall when we decided to cut aid.
Cut aid after we brought our troops out, the major forces.
We cut aid through congressional action.
That's physically how we really lost the war.
I don't believe that.
I believe Richard Nixon... Now, this is hindsight.
I could be wrong on this, but this is what I've heard before from...

either Channel 8 or one of these weird channels that I watch, educational channels, that was talking to either the ambassador or one of the top-ranking members of North Vietnam at the time about the bombing, a Christmas bombing, where they said, when solid thunder rolled over, those names, the OB-52, you hear about that, I know these huge terminology, but when they said the B-52s came over Hanoi,
During Christmas, during that time period, Nixon was, you know, letting bomb it.
They were told, one more day, we can't handle it anymore.
North Vietnam was to its knees.
The Christmas, there's a tremendous protest a few days before Christmas saying, Richard Nixon, you've got to stop bombing.
How cruel of you to bomb on Christmas Day.
Remember, Hanoi, they don't have Christmas.
You know, they have their other booths.
They have tests, which they blow the hell out of us on their holidays, you know.
But we weren't going to do it to them.
And they had a gigantic protest against Richard Nixon.
Richard Nixon backed down on Christmas Eve, and they said, Christmas Eve, if they bomb one more day, we'll sue for peace.
We can't handle those B-52s.
And he stopped.
And people have said, at that point, if he would have bombed one more day, the war would have been over with.
I don't believe him.
saying that Congress stopped it.
This war never had a chance.
You couldn't have won the war with 500,000 more, another million men in that country, because everything was corrupt.
We're playing politics.
If they would have gotten everybody out of there, got the press out and said, okay, Army, fight a war, it would take about a year.
But, of course, there wouldn't have been very many people left alive, but they would have fought the war.
Again, I feel sorry for the military generals
that were there because it's embarrassing.
They should have, they had the war won.
And politics messed up.
What was your opinion of the anti-war demonstrators?
One of the problems I feel that lost the war.
We've already talked about the military.
I don't blame the military for this problem.
I blame the State Department and the politicians.
Also, I look back
What lost the Vietnam War, we the Vietnamese should really go to and say, thank you very much, and North Vietnam should say, thank you very much, were the protesters.
I think that politicians were afraid of what was happening by high school, college, especially college students.
No one wants to die.
No one wanted to go to Vietnam.
We were wrong.
Politicians were wrong.
But I think the protesters did more harm than anything.
I'm not saying that protesting was wrong.
I think in this situation, I guess, we were wrong from the start.
And looking back, I'm saying, thank God we did have protesters, because we might still be in Vietnam fighting with a corrupt organization, a corrupt government still fighting that war.
But I blame, or I'd say that a lot of help for the end of the Vietnam War was protesters.
You're a veteran, and you retired.
the war was still going on.
Right.
What was your impression of the media coverage that was going on in the States because of your own frame of reference you would have as a veteran of the same conflict?
I dislike it.
I think a lot of the problems of the war, the military messed up on that.
The military did wrong, badly on that.
I mean, you can never say the military did something wrong.
They put a Dan Rather in Vietnam, not just one man, talking about in general.
What they did in Grenada, or Grenada,
is what they should have done.
After they have the battles, and they say, these are the pictures we want to show you.
We'll take the pictures.
We'll give you.

Whenever a person can wake up in the morning, or wake up, go to work, rush home at 6 o'clock in the evening, turn on Dan Rather or someone with CBS News saying, today, 2,000 men were injured, 500 were killed.
They don't realize that after a while, you get numb.
You're saying, my God, look how many people are dying.
And you
You start your own, and your morale goes way down.
The American public's morale has to die.
You're watching guys, you know, dirty.
I would go out for 60 days at times, and sometimes go out on patrol, hit a sweep or an operation, and I might be out for 60 days.
I've not come in.
I'm not taking a bath.
I had the same clothes on for 60 days.
I stink.
Some guy takes a picture of me, you know, saying, hi, are you having fun in Vietnam?
You know, they say, fuck you.
You know, we don't have anything to do with that guy.
But that's what they showed on television.
Dan Rather walked up to a guy on patrol being shot at saying, hi, are you having fun here?
Morality, you know, morale just dropped to, you know, zilch at that time.
But in World War II, the same thing happened.
If they would have gone to Iwo Jima and said, hey, are we having fun here?
You know, they would have gotten shot.
That is the difference.
They did not come out and say, 20,000 men were killed today in Iwo Jima.
Tomorrow might be 40,000 more.
That, I think, destroyed the war.
The morale of the United States just died because of TV coverage.
That's the military.
I blame them.
I hope they never do that again.
They just say, CBS, here are the pictures.
This is what you use.
If you don't like it, tough luck.
You mentioned earlier that the war turned bad in the 70s.
Right.
Because of the influx of personnel or... CBS.
I blame it.
Again, I fall back.
I am a total dislike for...
Major news.
Major news did not care about showing both sides.
Major news, all they wanted to do was either sell newspapers or sell primetime television to make commercials.
The more blood, the more guts, the more... And then when a person in high school or college sees this, and they see only CBS's liberal point of view, you are...
You're not brainwashing, but you're only showing one side.
And they're not showing, saying, hey, you know, there might be another side.
There might not have been at that time.
But they're frightening people.

And I think if I was in college at that time watching Dan Rather or whoever was on the CBS News at that time, later on the ABC started doing the same thing because everybody turned to CBS to watch the news.
They started doing the same thing, and they noticed their ratings went back up again.
I think that was unfair, very unfair, and I think that is one of the major causes.
I would have been totally afraid to go to Vietnam.
I would have ran to Canada because I know that, in my mind, that I had a feeling I am going to die, you know, and not everybody did die in Vietnam.
A lot of percentage did, but it frightened too many people.
I blame CBS.
